#Project Report

Title: Neural Correlates of Decision Making in Sensory Discrimination Tasks

Abstract

Understanding how sensory discrimination and decision-making processes are neutrally encoded is an important step in comprehending the more abstract problems of cognitive processing. Specifically, we aimed to uncover the inner workings of how decisions are made concerning the visual properties of stimuli. Using a large dataset of neuronal spike trains (each corresponding to an individual neuron) recorded in mouse V1 by Steinmetz et al. (2019), we explored how neural responses related to contrast level across different visual stimuli predict decision-making in a contrast-discrimination task. By studying neural responses to stimuli of different contrast levels and how these are correlated with the outcomes of a decision-making task performed by mice, we aimed to identify patterns of neural activity that are associated with successful versus unsuccessful decision. The specific analysis of the rich data concerning time-wise spike train recordings from four different mice across 18 sessions aimed at identifying how neurons in V1 encode information related to their visual property properties, such as different contrast levels, as well as decision-making regarding these. For this, we integrated analytical perspectives concerning spike trains with statistical methods aiming to uncover associations between specific patterns of neural activity and the outcomes of the decision-making process in mice. By uncovering such neural coding strategies and correlations during sensory discrimination and decision-making concerning the property of visual contrast, our study provides additional insights into the mechanisms underlying neural information processing in the visual cortex. This study may also help us understand how the brain supports decision-making in tasks where visual stimuli are used to assess whether a different property (such as visual contrast) is above or below a threshold.

I. Introduction

In science area, the question of how the brain computes sensory information to generate decisions is at the core of an important field of study. This project analyses the dataset created in Steinmetz et al. (2019), where authors recorded the neural activity of mice brains while engaging in perceptual discrimination of visual contrast. By analyzing spike train data coming from the visual cortex recorded under different visual stimulation, this paper aims to unveil the brain activity that allows a consistent decision under uncertain conditions and seal the gap between sensory information and behavior. This is particularly interesting to understand the neural correlates that underpin perceptual decisions, such as the distribution of neural activities between successes and failures in the perceptual decision task. It is assumed that such behavior would recruit appropriate neural substrates, which this paper aims to identify. To understand the neural code for sensory discrimination has potential implications for the development of neuroprotein devices and interventions for sensory processing disorders. This paper could improve the understanding of how brains make sensory discrimination decisions from neural activities fluctuating across different levels of confidence, and eventually foster a more holistic understanding of how the brain created a perceptual outcome from ambiguous sensory information.

3. Data Processing:

Because that we want aggregate dynamic signals, we need to calculate an average over trials, and a summary of the stochasticity in the stimuli contrasts. The lights fluctuate slowly across the plate, and any neuron’s spike rate would demonstrate a corresponding smooth variation. When data is grouped by its trial number, you should expect a visually consistent gradient in activity. Any raw recording, however, contains trial-by-trial noise that can obscure this regularity. Once again, it is necessary to conduct data processing. To demonstrate a few quantitative measures, we filled our dataset with variables that reflect experimental conditions related to the light versus dark contrast, as well as the type of feedback (which makes the fly’s task either easier or harder: chasing the light, or fleeing from it in a darker surround).

As each session selects different brain regions on different mice every trail, the brain regions cannot be used as the prior known information, and the average number of pulses from all brain regions at each moment is taken as the feature in order to allow the unification for the data from all sessions; contrast_diff is contrast_right-contrast_left, the difference for the left and right stimuli from different trials.

4. Analyzing Neural Responsiveness to Stimuli:

Our visualisation of changes in neuron spike rate tells us something about the subtle ways that the mice’s brains respond to slightly different visual inputs. We can see the given ranges of contrast differences reflected in this plot of neural activity arranged along the x-axis. And since we’ve ordered them with respect to the contrast difference, we can also see that the response is nonuniform across the mice. Not only are response dynamics different from an individual mouse to another, the response also changes in a way reflective of the strength and polarity of the visual contrast on the screen. Some trends emerge from our data. For example, an increase in neural firing rates can be seen with increasing contrast difference for mouse ‘Cori’. This suggests that her neurons respond more to large stimulus differences in a given trial.

On the other hand, we can see that the spike rates for ‘Hench’ do not seem to vary as much across contrast levels, so his neural responses may tend to be more uniform regardless of the intensity of the stimulus. This is useful for our model, because it suggests that it might be meaningful to use variables like neural firing rates in response to stimulus contrast to predict which trials a mouse will be correct in. Simply putting these averages together with the mice’s trial-success rates allows us to start painting a better picture of the kind of neural dynamics that might underlie how the mice make perceptual decisions. The provided data describes the proportion of each given contrast difference that the four mice experienced across the experimental block. The variable ‘contrast difference’ is calculated from the given contrasts presented on the left and the right screen.

The range of our provided seven possible contrast differences is (-1, -0.75, -0.5, -0.25, 0, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1).These reflect the range of stimulus differences that each mouse would experience between two choices, from one feature being far stronger to the other (represented by all values greater than 0), to the other being far stronger (represented by all values less than 0), and all the way through to the contrast being equal (this would be a value of 0).Each mouse has been put through this same experiment, where all have experienced trials consisting of the left MC being stronger than the right MC (represented by all values of negative numbers), the right MC being stronger than the left MC (represented by all values of positive numbers), and equal contrasts, (a value of 0).All of the mice have been exposed to the most extreme contrasts (those equal to -1 or 1) in the least diverse way possible – this would seem to be a natural occurrence because these are the cases where one MC must always be stronger than the other, which is likely least probable in an evenly balanced experiment.The centre value is a value of 0, where there is no difference in contrast, and all four mice have quite a good representation of this set of trials. This suggests that zero contrast would be what we would call a ‘no-difference trial’, there is nothing in the stimulus that gives the mouse a strong indication about which MC is stronger and, as such, this would be a trial where the animal rarely gives a ‘yes’ or ‘no’ response.This seems somewhat balanced across the mice, as all of the mice have been exposed to a wide range of contrast differences — there doesn’t seem to be any way in which one mouse would be exposed to one contrast difference far more than the others.

5. Visual the change of overall neuron spike rate for each session

To better visualise these neural dynamics, we next plotted the neuron spike rates in each session – the ups and downs of neural activity across individual trials. Each plot represents the behaviour of the neuron over these trials, and we can see that the variability of spikes across sessions is much higher than that within sessions. Such variability likely results from the complex underlying neural processes. Sometimes, spike rates peak and trough in such a way that we can imagine these plots representing the neural encoding of sensory experiences or decisions.

Some of the patterns that remain consistent across sessions might represent shared neural mechanisms, while the unique patterns of fluctuations might be related to individual differences or session-specific nuances. These insights, along with our earlier findings, can facilitate a more personalised revising of our predictive models of neural responsiveness in the face of this tapestry of variability across sessions.

The graphics describes the change in each trial by session over time in the overall neuron spike rate. We used the function in R to plot the mean spike rate of the neuron against the number of trials in each session. The black lines denote real spike rates across the trials while the blue line indicates in smoothed trend across the trials

Each session shows a substantial degree of variability in spike rates across trials. The variability could be due to the natural dynamics of neuronal firing patterns, or could be responding to some variable associated with different stimuli that are presented on different trials. Despite this variability, there is also some kind of stability in the range of spike rates with most sessions varying between 0 to 3 spikes in a trial with an occasional higher value. This suggests that though each individual trial may be responding differently, the overall state of the system is operating at a stable level of activity. In some of the sessions, the smoothed trend lines show an upward or downward drift, but in most cases, these drift lines are so weak that they are not especially conspicuous and might suggest that there is not a strong systematic change in neuron spike-rate as the sessions go by. Outliers: It is possible to see the presence of some spikes that are higher than anything else in a session and could be a result when the neurons were undergoing some activity in excess of what is normal. Such instances would be useful to look deeper into the conditions that would have led to such high spikes in activity , some behavioural response from the mice or some other factor influencing the neuronal activity. Session-to-session comparison: A close look at the plots would reveal that the nature of variability and trends are not exactly the same across sessions and this suggests that the way in which the mice are kept, the experimental set-up or the stimuli provided to the mice have session-to-session variation and can impact neuronal spike rates.

7. Visualize success rate change over time:

The success rate for each session is shown binned in 25-trial increments to help illustrate how outcomes can change over time. Success rates shown here have quite a bit of variation both across and within sessions, which reflects how dynamic the decision-making process might be. For some sessions, there is a clear pattern of increasing success rate which might reflect some slowly decreasing noise — that is, the process of learning or adaptation taking place. On other sessions, the success rate shows more of a variability. The specific trails might be mildly varying in difficulty, depending on the exact nature of the stimuli the mice receive. In other sessions, the variation might reflect mice themselves getting a bit shakier. A plot like this shows how events mimic a motion of updating an inner state, an ability to make correct decisions given a certain stimulus The binned nature of the success rate plots presents a slightly different view of trails, showing how often a particular etude looks good toward the end of a trial compared with how it looks at the midpoint.

The graphs below depict the rate of success for each session. It is plotted against the number of sessions completed, where we have 18 binned in 25 trials. For some sessions, there is a high initial rate of success that declines at a later stage. This might reflect an initial familiarity with the task that is then lost either due to fatigue or a reduced determination to try and complete the task. Some sessions tend to be much more stable in their performance and might reflect a degree of consistency in performance or that the task was matched to the level of ability of the mouse to perform the specific task.

Relative to the individual mice, Cori, Forssmann, Hench and Lederberg each have distinct patterns over time in terms of success rate: the line for Cori shows a decreasing slope, which would suggest a gradual diminishing in performance or even exhaustion with the trials; the line for Forssmann indicates a linear stability before it plummets in the last couple of trials; the pattern for Hench shows some fluctuations with considerable variance, which is suggestive of instability in performance or the difficulty of the task; Lederberg’s pattern has some mountain peaks and valleys, which is indicative of some conditions or times presenting more prone to the successful outcomes.

8. Dimension Reduction through PCA:

First PCA plot. PSO activity. A scatter of the first two principal components based on the neural activity data. Each dot represents the aggregated neural data for one single trial (technically a SQI here). The colour codes correspond to the session number: blue data points represent first session, red is the data for the second session. Although two PCs are projected here, it remains a bivariate data.Figure 2: Second PCA plot. PSO activity. Similar to the first plot, except here the data for the second principal component is plotted against the first one. The colour of the datapoints was adjusted to correspond with the resulting component colour here. Some intersession clustering is indicated, though there is some overlap which suggests commonalities in neural response across trials and sessions.The natural way to interpret such a plot is that the data interpret the information content and variance in the original set of data points. In particular. given that the points are more spread out along PC1 than PC2, we interpret the significance of PC1 by the breadth of the point spread here. In other words, there exists some common factor(s) responsible for the observed variability in neural recording patterns given by PC1, which discriminates what is captured from what is not by the first principal component. The point here is that PCA identifies some principal dimensions, akin to axes of a figurative space, that characterise within-session variability in neural recording. And while there is some old apparent intersession clustering, the overlap between sessions suggests commonalities in neural response patterns across diverse trials and sessions. This is a complex picture, but learning about session identifiers makes me suspect that independent neural response identifiers, be it by species or some other identifier of interest, could also exist across the mice in question. Now, if we combine this PCA insight with what we already learnt about the animal success rate over a period of time (from Table 1 above), it is plausible that the dimensions revealed by PCA relate to both neural activities and how these activities correlate with success, or failure, in trials.

The second PCA plot depicts the distribution of the trials based on the first two principal components of the neural activity data (the two axis motions). Each of the four mice – Cori, Forssmann, Hench and Lederberg – has a different color. Every single point in the picture corresponds to a trial, and their location is determined by the trial’s ‘transformed values’ on the two principle components PC1 and PC2, which capture the most significant sources of variability in the data. There is a significant spread into both the PC1 and PC2 axis directions, implying that these two components capture two distinct sources of variability of the secondary responses. Yet it also looks like the points are grouped by mouse, which correlates with the individual differences. Some mouse clusters are ‘cleaner’ (like the purple one for Hench), others are more dispersively mixed within (like the green one for Lederberg), perhaps due to differences in the consistency of the neural responses (direct translation of orientation stimuli) or due to the different effects of the experimental conditions on each mouse. This PCA analysis may help to characterise how each mouse’s brain activity is correlated with the experimental stimuli generated and the decisions made during each trial.

II. Data Integration

Each row of the data set represents a specific trial, and within each trial are several variables representing the different things measured in that trial – the experimental data from each mouse.

These are variables named :session_id: A unique identifier of a session. It is a very important variable from a temporal point of view that will allow detecting the temporal relationships among the recorded events.trials_id: A unique identifier of the trials (left and right responses separate). A crude analysis on individual trials is possible. This feature is crucial for the detection and characterisation of trial-by-trial dynamics.contrast_left: The level of contrast for the stimulus in the left visual field during a trial. Contrast is one of the salient feature of the stimuli, therefore a major suspect for manipulating the mouse decision.contrast_right: The level of contrast for the stimulus in the right visual field during a trial. Another salient feature of the stimuli, again a major suspect for influencing the mouse decision.contrast_diff: The difference between contrast_left and contrast_right. It is an indicator of the difference in the relative strength of the stimuli shown to the animal, and can be directly related to the decision process in the trials.mean_trail_spike: The mean number of spikes recorded from the neuron during a trial. The most relevant response variable in the trials.PC1 and PC2: The first two principal components obtained from the PCA plotted in the space of these features. These features are likely the neuron spike-counts in a few seconds time-bins.

These terms are dimensionality reductions of the input data that retain the most variance, and are used to reduce dimensionality (from grey matter size, blood volume and connectivity, to three values: age, gender, depression, etc, etc.) while retaining as much information as possible. The column “feedback labels” is a mapping from feedback type to binary outcomes (successes or failures) of each trial, where the original feedback types of 1 for ‘success’ and -1 for ‘failure’ has been transformed, with -1 mapped to 0 due to how binary classification algorithms are constructed.

III. Predictive Modeling

This stage of predictive modeling requires 80% of trials to be spent on training. I decide to try with xgboost and random forest because I have lots of features, I expect there are some interactions among those interactions, and I have a relative large training set to avoid overfitting. Training the model on more trials, the confidence increases for the model learning from the training data. While that may lead to better prediction and less error in the model, it also means the model will spend more time learning from the training data. By looking at the log losses over time, the model is learning the data and gets better at predicting the trial outcomes initially starting with 0.609173 and now down to 0.431106 by the 10 round of training. Log loss is a measure of how much information is needed to predict an event, and is typically considered the most valuable measure of how good your model is. It is also the cost of predicting an event. The lower the log loss, the better you’re doing at confiding in your predictions. We can see that this model will have a significant improvement in outcomes after running the tenth round . Trees are the learning algorithms we use in the models, and we get better with each additional tree. Here the trees are learning the data well and are able to predict the outcomes. Log losses over all 10 rounds of training.

True Negatives(TN): The model correctly predicted in 85 instances when the user feedback type was actually 0 (no expected behaviour change from the mouse). False positives(FP): In 46 instances the model incorrectly predicted the feedback type as 1, while it was actually 0.False negatives(FN): In 212 cases, the instancies were incorrectly predicted as 0 (feedback type), when they were actually 1. True positives(TP): The model correctly predicted 673 instances when the feedback type was actually 1.

These statistics shows us that in spite of slight bias towards False-negatives (mislabeling of some sucesfully completed trials), the model is basically more correct in the case of True-positives .It can be analysed through the graph from ROC (Receiver Operating Characteristic) analysis and the corresponding Area Under Curve (AUC) = 0.7719, which is a good robust score. An AUC of 1 would indicate a perfect test of the model. An AUC value of 0.5 means that there is no discriminatory power of the metric. Given an AUC score of 0.7719, it indicates a high ability to discriminate between the feedback type: this metric, which is independent of the threshold at which the classification is made, indicates that imaging done has a good measure of separability and to rank the cases above positive more consistently than the negative ones.

IV. Prediction Performance on the Test Sets

View the model’s performance metrics, which give us more nuanced ways to examine how well it predicted the feedback type for a user. These numbers provide evidence that the model is generally somewhat successful at making a difference between control occurrences (0) and case instances (1): accuracy for the model is 0.745

The confusion matrix provides a detailed breakdown of the model’s predictions: True Negatives (TN): There were 14 cases where the model classified feedback as type 0 (control), in cases where no change in behaviour was expected. False Positives (FP): In 41 case where the model has predicted the feedback type as 1 when it is in fact 0.Running the predictive model leads to a very high proportion of false positives, where the model fails to differentiate between controls and cases. It projects them both as cases. False Negatives (FN): In 10 cases, the model predicted the feedback type as 0 when they were actually 1, meaning cases of behaviour change were missed. True Positives (TP): The model correctly predicted 135 instances as feedback type 1, where behaviour change did occur.

The confusion matrix values show a model that is reasonably accurate, but is biased towards False Positives, meaning it appears prone to over-predicting at the expense of controls. This feature implies that a likely area for improvement is in reducing the model’s tendency to over-classify instances.

Aside from the Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) analysis, where the Area Under Curve (AUC) score is 0.6908, the model’s power can be further illustrated. An AUC score that approaches to 1 indicates complete modelling power, while a score that is close to 0.5 indicates modelling power not any better than chance. The AUC score of 0.6908 is only good, but not perfect, indicating that the model is able to body type-discriminate fairly well. This arises from the interpretation that the AUC of 0.6908 indicates that the model has an acceptable degree of separability in allowing for more consistent ranking of case instances above control instances than would random guessing.

V. Discussion

Working through the data and exploring which aspects of the neural activity benefited the performance of the predictive model gave rise to several insights. First, because of the dimensionality-reduction accomplished with PCA, the predictive model’s performance was better when the first two principal components were used instead of the full time-bin average counts across all 40 instantaneous time bins. This illustrates how useful dimensionality reduction is in machine learning: by using PCA, the variation that most clearly relates to and discriminates between the two types of feedBack was emphasised, effectively focusing the information, condensing what is relevant in terms of predictive power into few large components.

Second, we did well to use XGBoost – an algorithm capable of handling thousands of features and picking up complex relationships in the data. However, testing the Random Forest model might yield further benefits, as ensemble techniques are known to improve a model’s accuracy and reduce overfitting. When growing a decision tree, Random Forests take multiple samples of the data each time. They then apply these samples to different models to build multiple decision trees and average their predictions. This inherent randomness in how features and splits are selected could offer a different view of the data that might lead to different discoveries.

We could see is that when we look at the predictive accuracy of the model, there’s actually a variance with the session and experiment serial number: There’s something to be learned from the temporal dimension here. Maybe it’s some learning or fatigue effect that the mouse has; maybe it’s something due to changes in the setup with every next experiment – there could be some other temporal variance in the signal that we are recording. There could be some slightly different dynamics in neuronal response as the sessions progress.

session_id = 1:18;
mean_session_spike = 1:18;
region_count = 1:18;
unique_area = 1:18;
success_rate = 1:18;
for (i in 1:18) {
    spike = 0
    for (j in 1:length(session[[i]]$feedback_type)) {
    spike = spike + sum(session[[i]]$spks[[j]])
    }
    mean_session_spike[i] = spike / length(session[[i]]$brain_area)/length(session[[i]]$feedback_type);
    
    region_count[i] = length(session[[i]]$brain_area)
    unique_area[i]  = length(unique(session[[i]]$brain_area))
    success_rate[i] = mean(session[[i]]$feedback_type == 1);
}

session_tibble <- tibble("session_id" = session_id) %>%  add_column("mean_session_spike" = mean_session_spike) %>%  add_column("region_count" = region_count) %>%  add_column("unique_area" = unique_area) %>%  add_column("success_rate" = success_rate)
session_tibble

get_trail_data <- function(session_id, trail_id){
  spikes <- session[[session_id]]$spks[[trail_id]]
  if (any(is.na(spikes))){
    disp("value missing")
  }
 spikes_times_mean = matrix(colMeans(spikes), nrow = 1, ncol = 40) 
 spikes_times_mean = as.data.frame(spikes_times_mean)
  trail_tibble <-  tibble("session_id" = session_id) %>% add_column("mouse_name" = session[[session_id]]$mouse_name) %>% tibble("trail_id" = trail_id) %>% add_column("contrast_left"= session[[session_id]]$contrast_left[trail_id]) %>% add_column("contrast_right"= session[[session_id]]$contrast_right[trail_id])%>%  add_column("contrast_diff"= (session[[session_id]]$contrast_right[trail_id] - session[[session_id]]$contrast_left[trail_id])) %>%  add_column("mean_trail_spike"= mean(rowSums(spikes))) %>%  add_column("feedback_type"= session[[session_id]]$feedback_type[trail_id])
  trail_tibble = cbind(trail_tibble, spikes_times_mean)
  trail_tibble
}

trail_tibble <- get_trail_data(1,1)
for (i in 1:18) {
